<BaseLayout
  title="Pandas DataFrame Memory Optimizer — dtype Optimization Guide"
  description="Complete guide to reducing Pandas DataFrame memory usage with dtype downcasting, category types, sparse arrays, chunked reading, and memory_usage(). Save 50-80% memory on large datasets."
  tool="pandas-dtype-optimizer"
  faq={faq}
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Pandas DataFrame Memory Optimizer</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Reduce DataFrame memory by 50–80% using dtype downcasting, category types, sparse arrays, and chunked reading strategies.</p>
  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="text-green-500">✓ dtype downcasting</span>
    <span class="text-green-500">✓ category types</span>
    <span class="text-green-500">✓ sparse arrays</span>
    <span class="text-green-500">✓ chunked reading</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Why Pandas Memory Optimization Matters</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Pandas loads data into RAM, and the default dtype choices are conservative — every integer becomes int64 (8 bytes) and every float becomes float64 (8 bytes) regardless of actual value range. A dataset with 1 million rows and 20 columns can easily consume 1–2 GB under default settings when the same data could fit in 200 MB with proper dtype assignment.</p>
  <p class="mb-4">Memory pressure causes slow operations (data spills to swap), OOM crashes in production, and long load times. Optimizing dtypes is typically the highest-ROI performance improvement you can make to a data pipeline — it requires no algorithmic changes and benefits every downstream operation: groupby, merge, sort, and vectorized math all get faster when data fits in CPU cache.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Measuring Memory Usage Accurately</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Before optimizing, establish a baseline. The key is using <code>deep=True</code> in <code>memory_usage()</code> — without it, object columns are severely underreported.</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code set:html={memoryCheckExample}></code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">Always profile both before and after optimization to measure actual gains. The dtype column in <code>df.dtypes</code> is your map — int64 and float64 are candidates for downcasting, and object columns with low cardinality are candidates for category conversion.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Automatic Numeric Downcasting</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Pandas provides <code>pd.to_numeric(series, downcast='integer')</code> which scans the actual values and selects the smallest safe integer type. Combined with a simple utility function, you can automate optimization for entire DataFrames:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code set:html={downcastingExample}></code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">Integer type ranges to know:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">
    <li><code>int8</code> — -128 to 127 (1 byte)</li>
    <li><code>int16</code> — -32,768 to 32,767 (2 bytes)</li>
    <li><code>int32</code> — -2.1B to 2.1B (4 bytes)</li>
    <li><code>int64</code> — ±9.2 quintillion (8 bytes, Pandas default)</li>
    <li><code>float32</code> — 7 decimal digits precision (4 bytes)</li>
    <li><code>float64</code> — 15 decimal digits precision (8 bytes, Pandas default)</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="mb-4">Use float32 carefully — it loses precision for very large or very small values. For financial calculations requiring exact decimals, keep float64 or use Python's Decimal type.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Category dtype for Low-Cardinality Strings</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">The category dtype is Pandas' most powerful memory optimization for string data. It encodes unique values as integers internally and stores a tiny lookup table. A column with 1 million rows and only 5 unique values stores 1 million int8 codes instead of 1 million Python string objects.</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code set:html={categoryExample}></code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">The 5% rule is a practical heuristic — if the number of unique values is less than 5% of total rows, category is usually beneficial. Verify with actual memory measurements. Category also speeds up groupby and value_counts operations significantly because they operate on integer codes rather than string comparison.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Chunked Reading for Large Files</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">When a file is larger than available RAM, the chunked reader pattern processes data in batches without ever loading the full dataset. Combining chunked reading with explicit dtype specification minimizes peak memory per chunk:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code set:html={chunkedReaderExample}></code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">For aggregation tasks (sum, mean, count), the streaming pattern — process each chunk and accumulate results — avoids the need to concatenate chunks at all. For operations requiring random access across the full dataset, consider using Dask (which manages chunking transparently) or PyArrow (which supports memory-mapped files).</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Sparse Arrays for Mostly-Zero Data</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Sparse arrays are ideal for one-hot encoded matrices, user-item interaction matrices, or any column where most values are the same (zero, NaN, or False). Convert individual columns with:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code>{`import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Create sparse data (95% zeros)
data = np.zeros(1_000_000)
data[np.random.choice(1_000_000, 50_000, replace=False)] = 1.0

series_dense = pd.Series(data, dtype='float32')
series_sparse = pd.Series(data, dtype=pd.SparseDtype('float32', fill_value=0))

print(f"Dense:  {series_dense.memory_usage(deep=True) / 1024:.1f} KB")
print(f"Sparse: {series_sparse.memory_usage(deep=True) / 1024:.1f} KB")
print(f"Density: {series_sparse.sparse.density:.2%}")

# For a full DataFrame of sparse columns
from scipy.sparse import csr_matrix
# Convert to scipy sparse for sklearn compatibility
X_sparse = csr_matrix(df[feature_cols].values)`}</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Additional Memory Reduction Techniques</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>Drop unused columns immediately:</strong> Use <code>usecols</code> in read_csv or call <code>df.drop()</code> as soon as columns are confirmed unnecessary. Every column you load costs memory for its lifetime.</li>
    <li><strong>Use nullable integer dtypes:</strong> <code>pd.Int8Dtype()</code>, <code>pd.Int16Dtype()</code> etc. support NaN without converting to float. Useful when integer columns have missing values.</li>
    <li><strong>Parse dates properly:</strong> Store dates as datetime64[ns] (8 bytes) not as strings (object, 50–200 bytes per value). Pass <code>parse_dates=['col']</code> to read_csv.</li>
    <li><strong>Use boolean dtype:</strong> A boolean column stored as object uses ~50 bytes/row. As bool it uses 1 byte/row. Convert with <code>df['col'].astype(bool)</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Consider PyArrow backend:</strong> Pandas 2.0+ supports <code>dtype_backend='pyarrow'</code> in read_csv for Arrow-native memory layout, which can be significantly more efficient for large datasets with mixed types.</li>
    <li><strong>Delete intermediate DataFrames:</strong> Call <code>del df_temp</code> followed by <code>gc.collect()</code> after creating intermediate DataFrames in a pipeline to reclaim memory immediately.</li>
  </ul>

